What we just looked at is called a pooled model. It ignores the multilevel structure of the data.

Very rarely is it appropriate to model multilevel data with a pooled model.

ggplot(rnd_filter.df, aes(y = RNDIntensity, x = Year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(group = FirmID), alpha = 1/10) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE)

ggplot(rnd_filter.df, aes(y = ROS, x = Year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(group = FirmID), alpha = 1/10) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE)

ggplot(rnd_filter.df, aes(y = ROS, x = RNDIntensity)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  facet_wrap(~ SICCode)

\[y_{ij} = \beta_{0j} + \beta_{1j}x_{ij} + \epsilon_{ij}\]

With panel data, we are looking at two different effects of \(x\) on \(y\).

  • The within effect, which is the average effect of \(x\) on \(y\) for a given (average) \(j\) over observations \(i\)
  • The between effect, which is the average effect of \(x\) on \(y\) across \(j's\)

We can decompose \(x_{ij}\) into:

\[x_{ij}=\gamma_i+\tau_{ij}\]

For each \(x_{ij}\), there is going to be a between-component, \(\gamma\), that never changes for each \(i\) in the sample (the firm, for example). But there is also going to be a within-component, \(\tau\), that can change for each \(\gamma\) over \(i\) (the firm’s sales over time, for example).

\[y = \alpha + \beta{x} + \epsilon\]

By ignoring the multilevel structure with a pooled model, we are violating something called the i.i.d. assumption.

Given that each \(i\) occurs as a function of the \(j\) it nests under, we assume that there is some type of clustering of each \(i\) around its respective \(j\). If this is true, then our OLS estimator will be inconsistent.

So we have to use a different approach, and the choice depends on a couple of things…

  • The structure of the data

  • Whether we are interested in within effects, betweeen effects, or both

  • Whether meaningful predictors exist at multiple levels (\(i\) and \(j\))

  • The relationship between \(i\)’s and their corresponding \(j\)’s

The relationship between \(i\)’s and their corresponding \(j\)’s

This part is the hardest. Particularly when unobserved variables at the \(i\) level correlates with their \(j\).

Just like our other omitted variable problems, if we don’t capture all of the meaningful variables that might cause \(i\)’s to correlate with their \(j\)’s, our model will produce biased results.

Fortunately in multilevel data, there are some shortcuts to help us deal with this source of bias.

Correctly modeling multilevel data is, well, hard.

We’re going to jump right in with something called a Random Intercept/Random Slope Within-Between Multilevel Model.

Level 1 \[y_{ij} = \beta_{0j} + \beta_{1j}x_{ij} + \epsilon_{ij}\]

  • \(y_{ij}\) = Value of the \(i^{th}\) observation of \(y\) for the \(j^{th}\) entity
  • \(\beta_{0j}\) = The value of \(y\) (intercept) for the \(j^{th}\) entity
  • \(\beta_{1j}\) = The expected change in \(y\) (slope) for a one unit change in \(x\) for the \(j^{th}\) entity
  • \(x\) = Value of the \(i^{th}\) observation of \(x\) for the \(j^{th}\) entity
  • \(\epsilon_{ij}\) = The variance in the \(i^{th}\) observation of \(y\) for the \(j^{th}\) entity that is not explained by the Level 1 equation (sometimes called \(r_{ij}\))

Level 2

\[\beta_{0j} = \gamma_{00} + u_{0j}\]

  • \(\gamma_{00}\) = The overall intercept, also called the grand mean; the expected value of \(y\) for all \(i,j\) observations when all Level 1 and Level 2 predictors equal zero
  • \(u_{0j}\) = The deviation in the intercept for the \(j^{th}\) entity from the overall intercept (\(\gamma_{00}\))

\[\beta_{1j} = \gamma_{10} + u_{1j}\]

  • \(\gamma_{10}\) = The expected change in \(y\) for an average \(j\) across observations \(i\)
  • \(u_{1j}\) = The deviation in the slope for the \(j^{th}\) entity from the overall (average) slope (\(\gamma_{10}\))

Fixed effects, random effects, and the difference between economics and, well, everyone else.

In multilevel models, what we are really after is understanding different types of variance occurring at different levels.

We’re trying to quantity uncertainty around the effect of \(x\) on \(y\) that is because of differences within and between \(j\) groups.

Variances

  • \(\sigma^2\) = Estimated within-group variance (\(\epsilon_{ij}\))
  • \(\tau_{00}\) = Estimated between-group variance (\(u_{0j}\))
  • \(\tau_{11}\) = Estimated random-slope variance (\(u_{1j}\))
  • \(\rho_{01}\) = Estimated random-intercept / random-slope correlation
  • ICC = Inter-class correlation coefficient

The ICC is pretty useful…it tells you the extent to which, on average, observations within a \(j\) correlate with each other.

The higher the ICC, the “more important” the multilevel structure.

So that’s hard to interpret. Fortunately with a little wrangling, we can split the within and between components of \(x\), and in the process, deal with a major omitted variable concern.

We’re going to do something called group mean centering.

rnd_filter.df <- rnd_filter.df %>% 
  group_by(FirmID) %>% 
    mutate(meanRNDIntensity = mean(RNDIntensity), 
           cenRNDIntensity = RNDIntensity - meanRNDIntensity)

The meanRNDIntensity variable is called panel invariant, because it takes on the same value for all of \(j\)’s observations…

rnd_filter.df %>% 
  filter(FirmID == 1820) %>% 
  select(cenRNDIntensity, meanRNDIntensity)
## # A tibble: 5 x 3
## # Groups:   FirmID [1]
##   FirmID cenRNDIntensity meanRNDIntensity
##    <dbl>           <dbl>            <dbl>
## 1   1820           0.538             6.86
## 2   1820          -0.290             6.86
## 3   1820           0.480             6.86
## 4   1820          -0.443             6.86
## 5   1820          -0.285             6.86

The cenRNDIntensity variable has a mean of 0 within each \(j\), which makes each observation a deviation from the meanRNDIntensity variable.

rnd_filter.df %>% 
  filter(FirmID == 1820) %>% 
  summarise(myMean = mean(cenRNDIntensity))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   FirmID    myMean
##    <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1   1820 -3.55e-16

So now lets fit a new model…

library(lme4)
wb.model <- lmer(ROS ~ cenRNDIntensity + meanRNDIntensity + 
                   (cenRNDIntensity + meanRNDIntensity | FirmID), 
                 data = rnd_filter.df)

tab_model(wb.model)
  ROS
Predictors Estimates CI p
(Intercept) 2.65 -5.12 – 10.42 0.504
cen RND Intensity -1.58 -2.34 – -0.83 <0.001
mean RND Intensity -0.41 -0.87 – 0.05 0.082
Random Effects

τ11 FirmID.cenRNDIntensity 2.07
τ11 FirmID.meanRNDIntensity 1.34
ρ01 FirmID.cenRNDIntensity 1.00
ρ01 FirmID.meanRNDIntensity -0.86
ICC FirmID 0.83
Observations 319

The estimate for cenRNDIntensity is the within effect, estimating the expected change in ROS for an average firm over time.

The estimate for meanRNDIntensity is the between effect, estimating the expected change in ROS across firms and over time.

In our model, the within-firm effect seems to be a major source of the variance in ROS associated with R&D Intensity, as compared to the between-firm effect.

With WB-MEM models, we can add even more levels, but that’s for another time.

wb.ts.model <- lmer(TestScore ~ cenTrainingTime + meanTrainingTime +
